The [Prime Minister of Pakistan](/wiki/Prime_Minister_of_Pakistan "Prime
Minister of Pakistan") ([Urdu](/wiki/Urdu_language "Urdu language"): **وزِیرِ
اعظم** ‬‎ — __Wazīr-ē Aʿẓam__ , Urdu pronunciation: [[ʋəˈziːr-ˌeː
ˈɑː.zəm]](/wiki/Help:IPA/Hindi_and_Urdu "Help:IPA/Hindi and Urdu"); [Turkish
lit.](/wiki/Turkish_Language "Turkish Language") "[Grand
Vizier](/wiki/Grand_Vizier "Grand Vizier")"), is the
[popularly](/wiki/Landslide_victory "Landslide victory")
[elected](/wiki/Elections_in_Pakistan "Elections in Pakistan")
[politician](/wiki/Political_leader "Political leader") who is the [chief
executive](/wiki/Chief_executive_officer "Chief executive officer") of the
[Government](/wiki/Government_of_Pakistan "Government of Pakistan") of
[Pakistan](/wiki/Pakistan "Pakistan").[1] The Prime Minister is vested with
the [responsibility](/wiki/Moral_responsibility "Moral responsibility") of
running the [administration](/wiki/Government_administration "Government
administration") through his appointed [federal
cabinet](/wiki/Cabinet_of_Pakistan "Cabinet of Pakistan"), formulating
national policies to ensure the safeguard of the
[interests](/wiki/National_interest "National interest") of the nation and its
people through the [Council of Common
Interests](/wiki/Council_of_Common_Interests "Council of Common Interests") as
well as making the decision to call nationwide [general
elections](/wiki/Elections_in_Pakistan "Elections in Pakistan") for the
[bicameral](/wiki/Bicameralism "Bicameralism") [Parliament of
Pakistan](/wiki/Parliament_of_Pakistan "Parliament of Pakistan").[2][3][4]

Since 1947, Pakistan has had eighteen prime ministers, aside from the
appointed [caretaker prime
ministers](/wiki/Caretaker_Prime_Minister_of_Pakistan "Caretaker Prime
Minister of Pakistan") who were only mandated to oversee the system until the
election process was finished. In Pakistan's [parliamentary
system](/wiki/Parliamentary_system "Parliamentary system"), the Prime Minister
is [sworn-in](/wiki/Oath_of_Office "Oath of Office") by the
[President](/wiki/President_of_Pakistan "President of Pakistan") and usually
is the [Chairman](/wiki/Party_chair "Party chair") or/ the
[President](/wiki/President_\(corporate_title\) "President \(corporate
title\)") of the [party](/wiki/Pakistani_political_parties "Pakistani
political parties") or [coalition](/wiki/Coalition_government "Coalition
government") that has a [majority](/wiki/Majority "Majority") in the [National
Assembly](/wiki/National_Assembly_of_Pakistan "National Assembly of
Pakistan")– the [lower house](/wiki/Lower_house "Lower house") of [Pakistan
Parliament](/wiki/Pakistan_Parliament "Pakistan Parliament").

After the [Partition of India](/wiki/Partition_of_India "Partition of India")
on the midnight of 14/15 August 1947, Pakistan followed the [British
system](/wiki/British_parliamentary_system "British parliamentary system") by
creating the post of Prime Minister based at the [Prime Minister's
Secretariat](/wiki/Prime_Minister%27s_Secretariat_\(Pakistan\) "Prime
Minister's Secretariat \(Pakistan\)").[3][4] The then [Governor-General of
Pakistan](/wiki/Governor-General_of_Pakistan "Governor-General of Pakistan"),
[Muhammad Ali Jinnah](/wiki/Muhammad_Ali_Jinnah "Muhammad Ali Jinnah"), took
advice from the [Founding Fathers of the
nation](/wiki/Founding_Fathers_of_Pakistan "Founding Fathers of Pakistan") and
appointed [Liaquat Ali Khan](/wiki/Liaquat_Ali_Khan "Liaquat Ali Khan") to
establish and lead his [administration](/wiki/Ali_Khan_administration "Ali
Khan administration") on 15 August 1947.[5] Before the [presidential
system](/wiki/Constitution_of_Pakistan_of_1962 "Constitution of Pakistan of
1962") in 1960, seven prime ministers had served between 1947 until [martial
law in 1958](/wiki/1958_Pakistani_coup_d%27%C3%A9tat "1958 Pakistani coup
d'état"). In 1971, the office was again revived but ceased to exist
shortly.[6][7] Executive powers and authority was given to the Prime Minister
when the full set of the [Constitution of
Pakistan](/wiki/Constitution_of_Pakistan "Constitution of Pakistan") was
promulgated in 1973 but the post was ceased from its effective operations
after another [martial law in 1977](/wiki/1977_Pakistani_coup_d%27%C3%A9tat
"1977 Pakistani coup d'état").[8][9] After the [general
elections](/wiki/Pakistani_general_election,_1985 "Pakistani general election,
1985") held in 1985, the office came to its existence.[6] Between 1988–99, the
office was held by [Benazir Bhutto](/wiki/Benazir_Bhutto "Benazir Bhutto") of
the [PPP](/wiki/Pakistan_Peoples_Party "Pakistan Peoples Party") and [Nawaz
Sharif](/wiki/Nawaz_Sharif "Nawaz Sharif") of
[PML(N)](/wiki/Pakistan_Muslim_League_\(N\) "Pakistan Muslim League \(N\)"),
each holding the office for two non-consecutive terms between 1988 and 1999:
Bhutto during 1988–90 and 1993–96;[10] and Sharif during 1990–93 and
1997–99.[11][12]

The premiership of [I. I. Chundrigar](/wiki/I._I._Chundrigar "I. I.
Chundrigar") was the shortest in [Pakistan's
history](/wiki/History_of_Pakistan "History of Pakistan"), serving only 55
days of his term. At approximately five years and four months in total, Sharif
is the longest-serving Prime Minister.[3][13] Sharif was re-elected for a
third non-consecutive term on 5 June 2013, which is a record in the [history
of Pakistan](/wiki/History_of_Pakistan#State_and_Constitution:_Pakistan
"History of Pakistan").[14][15] The [national
politics](/wiki/Politics_in_Pakistan "Politics in Pakistan") in Pakistan was
mostly dominated by the [army department](/wiki/Pakistan_Army "Pakistan Army")
of the [Pakistan Armed Forces](/wiki/Pakistan_Armed_Forces "Pakistan Armed
Forces") throughout its history, but it is now dominated by the political
parties.[16]

After the [general elections](/wiki/Pakistani_general_election,_2002
"Pakistani general election, 2002") held in 2002, [Zafarullah Khan
Jamali](/wiki/Zafarullah_Khan_Jamali "Zafarullah Khan Jamali") was invited to
form his [administration](/wiki/Jamali_administration "Jamali administration")
as its Prime Minister.[16] After the [Supreme Court of
Pakistan](/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_Pakistan "Supreme Court of Pakistan")'s
rulings to disqualified the Prime Minister [Yousaf Raza
Gillani](/wiki/Yousaf_Raza_Gillani "Yousaf Raza Gillani") in 2012, the
business of his [administration](/wiki/Gillani_ministry "Gillani ministry")
was looked after by [Pervez Ashraf](/wiki/Raja_Pervez_Ashraf "Raja Pervez
Ashraf") until the [caretaker administration](/wiki/Khoso_caretaker_ministry
"Khoso caretaker ministry") was setup under [Mir Hazar
Khoso](/wiki/Mir_Hazar_Khan_Khoso "Mir Hazar Khan Khoso").[17][18][3][4]
